Any work of the MirOS Project is licenced as a compilation, subject
to the following terms and conditions:
d55 27
a81 38
vered by individual licence clauses.  The collection divides into:
o the BSD-based operating system (aka MirBSD(TM))
	consisting of a 4.4BSD derived operating system base,
	as well as some additional code e.g. from the GNU project
o the Linux-based operating system (aka MirLinux or ecce!Linux v2)
	consisting of the same base system MirBSD(TM) is built of,
	in addition the Linux kernel, the GNU libc and GNU make, as
	well as some other kernel-dependent programmes
o the MirPorts framework
	based upon the OpenBSD ports tree, but not being part of the
	base system, provides a defined way to install and possibly
	deinstall third-party software into MirOS.


The MirOS Project tries to provide a full open source operating sy-
stem environment, to anybody interested, free of charge and with as
few restrictions on general usage and redistribution as possible. A
defined way to install and uninstall third-party applications which
are not contained within the base installation, the MirPorts frame-
work, is also developed; for this purpose the "MirPorts Team" squad
has been formed.
The names "MirBSD" and "MirLinux" are deprecated for denoting MirOS
BSD and MirOS Linux. Note that MirOS Linux contains more code under
a licence requiring you to redistribute modifications you made with
the system itself, than the main base system (MirOS BSD). Please do
note that the MirPorts framework itself is licenced under the terms
above, but anything it acts and applies to third-party applications
(including "forward ed diffs") is considered "fair use" and doesn't
make MirPorts a derived work of the referred works. Unified contex-
tual diffs are a derived work of the patched file; thus they aren't
part of MirPorts, nor subject to its licence, but to the licence of
the patched file.)


Most other work in the base install is licenced under the terms and
conditions below. Several of the named authors have removed or cea-
sed to enforce the third (advertising) clause; we didn't remove the
clause in the text below for reference though.
a408 10
Portions of this compilation (the whole GNU stuff, sendmail) impose
certain limitations not covered here.  You are required to read, un-
derstand and acknowledge the licences of these tools prior to using
them.  These files can be found in /usr/share/doc/legal after in-
stalling the baseXX.tgz installation set.
An overview of these conditions is installed as /usr/share/doc/legal/LICENCE
Other portions, such as the Apache web server, do not really re-
strict, but rather require that derivated works are named diffe-
rently, that's why they are not listed here.

