text
@d1 1
a1 1
# $MirBSD: COPYRIGHT,v 1.17 2003/12/03 19:24:31 tg Exp $
d5 3
a7 3
This is licence info centre for the MirOS advanced operating system
project, its offspring are the operating system variants MirBSD and
MirLinux ("MirOS BSD/Linux") as well as the MirPorts framework.
a8 45
The MirOS project consists of the following three compilations:
o the BSD-based operating system (aka MirBSD(TM))
	consisting of a 4.4BSD derived operating system base,
	as well as some additional programmes
o the Linux-based operating system (uka MirLinux)
	consisting of the same base system MirBSD(TM) is built of,
	the Linux kernel, the GNU libc and GNU make, as well as
	some other kernel-dependent programmes
o the MirPorts framework
	based upon the OpenBSD ports tree, but not being part of the
	base system, provides a defined way to install and possibly
	deinstall third-party software into MirOS.

MirOS strives to provide an operating system open to everybody, with
as few restrictions as possible, and simple licence terms.
This is achieved by providing MirBSD to the general public.

MirOS also provides a Linux-based operating system still open for
everybody to use and redistribute, but - due to upstream package
decisions - imposes certain restrictions (namely, the force to re-
distribute source code) which touch MirBSD only tangentially (the
GNU compiler toolchain, which is not considered part of the base
system, and a few utilities) on a large part of the base system, so
it's probably not the best choice for commercial use (redistribu-
tion; usage in a company is unrestricted).

MirOS provides a freely available framework, the MirPorts system,
whose components are Makefiles, packaging informational files and
patches to the programmes installed.  The MirPorts general frame-
work is available under a BSD-style licence.
In contrast, patches usually contain code lines of third-party
software, and thus unified, context and other non-unidirectional
diff formats must be considered licenced by the same conditions as
the original file it applies to.  Unidirectional ed diffs, however,
are freely available under the same conditions as the MirPorts
framework.
Using the MirPorts systen to install third-party applications is
considered fair use - however, in most cases you cannot freely
redistribute the result ("package"), and in some cases, there are
restrictions imposed on distributing or even downloading the source.

The MirPorts system tries to validate the integrity of downloaded
third-party sources ("distfiles") by applying checksums, however,
there is no defined way the porter can check these before making a
port, and there is no warranty whatsoever.
d10 2
d13 2
a14 3
The MirOS compilations are covered by the following conditions:

 * Copyright (c) 2002, 2003: The MirOS Project
d22 1
a22 1
 * fy, publically perform, give away, merge or sublicense it provided
d27 1
a27 1
 * ties whatsoever to the maximum extend permitted by applicable law;
d31 10
a40 1

d42 3
a44 1
 * of Germany; place of court is Bonn. (Gerichtsstand ist Bonn.)
a45 16
To the maximum extent of the editors knowledge, the MirOS system
does not contain malicious code or code which is intellectual pro-
perty of third parties.  However, both human knowledge and software
quality are limited - please be assured there is no intent to di-
stribute buggy or non-free code.  - The MirPorts tree has already
been talked about above.


The MirOS system includes work of other parties, which usually was
integrated under a 4-clause UCB-style licence.  Many authors have
since decided the third clause to be rescinded; for the sake of
completeness, it's still included below.
The MirOS team disclaims all liability for work of others licenced
to the user. We try to check with all authors and contributors for
correctness of what we include, but we can't guarantee correctness
for other peoples' work ourselfes.
d47 13
a59 8
Portions of this compilation (the whole GNU stuff, sendmail) impose
certain limitations not covered here.  You are required to read, un-
derstand and acknowledge the licences of these tools prior to using
them.  These files can be found in /usr/share/doc/legal after in-
stalling the baseXX.tgz installation set.
Other portions, such as the Apache web server, do not really re-
strict, but rather require that derivated works are named diffe-
rently, that's why they are not listed here.
